Management of sales tax in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany
Review report
Preface
Taxes are the main source of income for public households.
An emphasis of the activities of the accounting offices should therefore be on the examination of this area.
This applies in particular to sales tax fraud.
This alone creates tax losses of an estimated Eur1 100 billion per year in the European Union.
Already at VI. EUROSAI Congress 2005 in Bonn pointed out the need for enhanced cooperation.
This allows the accounting offices to: B. Exchange test approaches and optimize test practice.
The VAT (VAT) is particularly suitable for cooperation as it is harmonised within the European Union.
In 2006, the accounting offices of both states checked concurrently for the first time in the UST area.
The corresponding audit report was published in 2008.
Since USt fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, close cooperation between the accounting offices is needed. This can fully assess whether the measures taken are capable of effectively addressing USt fraud.
The two accounting offices decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel audit. Management of sales tax in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany Report on Control Audit
1. Introduction
Examination number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892
Exam object: (CZ) Administration of the USt (D) Bilateral audit with the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter referred to as NKÚ), verification audit
Exam aim:
(CZ) The USt administration and the treatment of selected transactions between operators of the Czech Republic (hereinafter CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter Germany) should be examined. Furthermore, the procedures used by the financial authorities in intergovernmental assistance should be examined.
(D) The audit should assess how the financial management has implemented the recommendations made by the accounting offices.
In addition, additional test fields linked to the USt should be edited.
The findings made should be compared in order to determine whether the taxation procedures can be optimized.
The audit period was between 2006 and 2008, including relevant information from the period before the examination period until the completion of the audit.
2. Summary of results and evaluation of the parallel test
The accounting offices of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed to carry out an audit of the administration of the USt.
During the previous parallel test, they had uncovered suspected cases involving intra-Community turnover,
Which appeared to be a temporary test improper.
Due to audit findings, the two accounting offices made recommendations on the administration of the USt.
The aim of the inspection was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented. In addition, the suspected cases found should be investigated.
The examination also dealt with other facts. These included selected cases of intra-Community risk, mutual administrative assistance in the recovery of UST claims and UST audit in large enterprises.
In doing so, the accounting offices found:
1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous audit
• Recommendation 1: The rules for the registration of taxpayers should be harmonised within the EU
In the initial audit, the accounting offices compared registration procedures to the USt in the two states and noted differences that caused problems.
The Court of Auditors therefore recommended that the registration of taxpayers within the EU be harmonised.
This has also been taken up at EU level.
The draft revision of Council Regulation No 1798/2003 provides for the extension of the current databases in the EU, including a database with the UST obligation identification number.
The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxpayers and their eventual deletion.
The accounting offices expected Member States to agree on appropriate arrangements in accordance with their policy decision to remove unreliable entrepreneurs from the UST system as early as possible.
Member States reached political agreement in the ECOFIN on the final version of the draft.
These common rules are no longer included in them. The two accounting offices regret that.
They still consider such arrangements important to prevent sales tax fraud.
• Recommendation 2: Monthly submission of summary reports As a result of the initial audit, the accounting offices recommended to the Member States that the summary notifications (ZM) be submitted on a monthly basis in the future.
The amounts of intra-Community transactions could then be reviewed in a timely manner.
Council Directive 2008/117/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of value added tax for the purpose of combating the fraud of intra-Community transactions has reduced the time limit for the levy of ZM to one month.
In the CZ, this provision was introduced by a 1. January 2010 implemented into force novella of the USt Act.
In Germany, the implementation did not take place until 1. It entered into force on 1 July 2010. As a result, it has not transposed into national law the obligation to submit the ZM on a monthly basis.
• Recommendation 3: The German Financial Administration has taken up the recommendation made by the Federal Court of Auditors and set up a working group to develop possible solutions.
Work has not yet been completed.
The Federal Court of Auditors will observe the further development.
• Recommendation 4: Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches to a risk management system at EU level During the first audit, the two accounting offices agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by a Member State alone.
Successful criteria and elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU Member State.
If this is not done, fraudsters will focus on the Member State with the weakest risk management system.
The audit offices found that the two Member States apply different risk management systems that have both strengths and weaknesses.
The NKU reviewed the system of exchange of information within the EU - EUROCANET, while the Federal Court of Auditors focused on German participation in the "Platform for Risk Management."
2. Verification of selected intra-Community transactions
The accounting offices had jointly examined transactions during the initial audit, in which it was doubtful whether they had actually been exported or which had been explained differently by the taxpayer of the two states in the USt pre-declarations (or USt declarations) or ZM respectively.
The accounting offices selected nine cases of intra-Community supplies of goods between the CZ and Germany for the inspection.
The audits by the Financial Offices (CMO) of both States had not yet ended at the conclusion of the first parallel audit.
The audit showed that the tax procedures for these selected transactions have now been completed. The respective financial administrations had taken appropriate measures to do so (including: Subsequent USt fixtures or the prevention of pre-tax refunds).
3. Audit of selected intra-Community transactions that are particularly risk-sensitive
The audit also included strong intra-Community transactions between taxpayers in the EU covered by EUROCANET.
EUROCANET is used to identify eligible taxable persons.
Member States may participate in this system on a voluntary basis.
The CZ is an active participant in EUROCANET. Germany has passive status, d. That is, it does not participate in data exchange under EUROCANET.
From the point of view of an active participating State, it is unsatisfactory for other Member States to refuse to participate actively.
This failed to obtain information about which suppliers with German USt-ID would have been classified as highly risk-driven cases.
The NKU placed both normal business incidents and those with suspicion of USt fraud in the selected transactions, including: Carousel fraud, firm.
The CMO was only able to examine high-risk transactions in a limited manner. This was particularly true in so-called "missing traders," where an examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to prove fraud to the taxable person.
Suspected of carousel fraud in the case of imports and exports
It is recommended that customs and tax authorities cooperate more closely in order to monitor the nature of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final customer.
Germany, as well as a number of other countries, have refused to participate actively in EUROCANET as there is no sufficient legal basis from their point of view.
The Federal Court of Auditors found that the German Financial Administration uses other instruments to detect vulnerable taxpayers.
However, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU Member States.
The EU Council agreed on a draft regulation:
Which has been created.
The experience gained with EUROCANET so far should be included in the planned network for combating UST fraud.
4. Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims shall be subject to the same European legislation in all Member States.
Therefore, requests for intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the CZ and Germany are dealt with in the same way.
Bundesrechnungshof and NKU compared the statistics sent to the European Commission by both Member States for the years 2006 to 2008.
These statistics contained inconsistencies.
The two Court of Auditors consider that a renewed discussion of statistics at EU level makes sense in order to avoid any remaining inconsistencies in the future.
If this is not done, the statistics cannot be adequately used for comparisons.
In addition, the statistics should contain more information on the UST.
An analysis of detailed data may make it easier for the Commission to assist Member States in their efforts to combat UST fraud.
Both accounting institutions consider that Member States with a low rate of recovery should endeavour to achieve at least the average rate of recovery.
The Commission should assist the Member States in doing so if this is desired.
5. USt testing for large enterprises
The accounting offices analysed the legal situation regarding the USt audit of large enterprises in both states.
In addition, they collected information from the financial administrations with a questionnaire, which they considered important in this context.
In doing so, it was clear that the situation is different in both states.
The CZ has a system that includes a large number of relevant data (including: Information on USt tests, balance sheet data and profit and loss accounts).
Overall, USt control can be effectively controlled and analyzed.
A Special Financial Office for Large Enterprises is to be established in 2012.
There is no comparable system yet in Germany. This makes it difficult to control and analyze the overall USt control.
The German financial management focuses more on the selection of relevant individual cases and is based in particular on data from the USt pre-declarations or USt declarations and the ZM.
Various risk management components to be improved support the evaluation of these data.
