4. Audit of the management of sales tax in selected areas
4.1 Implementation of the recommendations from the first joint audit
4.1.1 Implementation of the recommendations in the Czech Republic
Recommendation 1
Harmonisation of conditions for registration of taxpayers within the EU Supported
On the results of the first audit, the Czech Court of Auditors recommended that the requirements for VAT registration be adjusted and that new rules for the deletion of registration in the CZ be introduced.
These amended rules should more effectively curb the risk of possible tax evasion.
In certain cases, it was found that, if they did not comply with their obligations under Czech Law No 235/2004 (hereinafter referred to as the UST Act), the CMO did not delete the VAT registration of taxable persons.
So far, the Czech Ministry of Finance has not submitted a novelisation to oblige the CMO to delete if taxpayers do not repeatedly file UST statements.
Under the Czech UST Act, the FA may delete the registration of a taxable person of its own motion if (a) the taxable person did not make transactions during 12 consecutive months and the FA did not inform the reasons for that; B) the taxable person has failed to fulfil his obligations under the UST law; (C) the taxable person no longer meets the conditions for the tax obligation.
The first examination showed that due to the existing legal situation, the FA Prague 1 the UST registration of "foreign taxable persons" 3 with effect from the 31. Must delete January of the following calendar year if they were not required to register and pay USt during the current calendar year.
The FA Prague 1 often did not delete the UST registration of these taxpayers because the relevant provision of the deadline could not be adequately implemented in practice.
The problem was solved by the novelization of the USt Act, which was issued on 1 July. It entered into force on January 1, 2009.
Consequently, the FA is entitled to delete the registration of a foreign taxable person if he has not provided any taxable or exempt supplies of goods or services entitled to deduction during the preceding calendar year.
Recommendation 2
Monthly levy of ZM
Due to the initial audit, the accounting offices had recommended that the monthly levy of ZM be introduced.
The Council Directive, which reduced the turnus to one month for the ZM to be issued, was adopted in the CZ by the CZ on 1 July. UST Law, which entered into force in January 2010.
The ZM must now be delivered electronically.
In addition, a ZM must be provided if services whose place of performance is to be determined in accordance with Section 9 (1) of the UST Act are provided for a person registered in another Member State as subject to VAT.
This requires the recipient to declare and pay the UST for these services. This obligation follows from Council Directive 2008/8/EC amending Directive 2006/112/EC as regards the place of supply of services.
Recommendation 3
Comparison of the data of the USt pre-declarations and the ZM to increase the reliability of MIAS data This recommendation referred to the German financial management.
In its ATIS4 system, Czech financial management automatically assigns data on intra-Community transactions from the UST declarations and the ZM.
Recommendation 4
Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches to a risk management system at EU level
The proper collection of the USt is an essential prerequisite for the smooth functioning of the EU internal market.
That is why the fight against USt fraud is of primary interest and has received considerable attention in recent years.
The importance of this is evidenced, inter alia, by an investigation published by the European Commission in October 2009.
An external expert estimated the UST failure for the 25 Member States over the period 2000 to 2006. After evaluation of the available data, the tax outage was estimated at between EUR 90 billion and EUR 113 billion for the said period. It was based on the fact that the EU-25 loses an average of 12% of their turnover taxes each year.
The estimated tax outage for the CZ was 18% in 2006.
The first examination found that a Member State alone cannot develop an effective risk management system (RMS).
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each Member State.
In relation to the RMS, the Czech Court of Auditors examined the system for the exchange of information within the EU (EUROCANET).
For this purpose, intra-Community transactions carried out by taxpayers within the EU and covered by EUROCANET have been selected (see chapter 4.3).
It aims to optimize administrative assistance in tax matters and to combat USt fraud more effectively. The cooperation of the competent authorities is to be improved in order to identify fraud as early as possible.
Later, it could be used as a tool to estimate the risk potential of intra-Community sales.
The ECOFIN-Rat6 was released on 7 July. Approved October 2008 while adopting the principles for the functioning of the system.
EUROCANET, which has been developed by the Belgian Financial Administration in cooperation with the other Member States, and with the support of the European Commission and STF7, serves as a role model for it.
The purpose of the system is to detect risk-related transactions and identify entrepreneurs involved in organized USt fraud.
