4.2 Verification of selected intra-Community transactions
The first audit examined jointly transactions which raised doubts as to whether they had actually been carried out or whether inconsistencies had been found in the reports of taxpayers in both Member States.
The two audit offices selected nine cases of intra-Community supplies of goods between the CZ and Germany for the verification, in which the tax audit by the Member State concerned had not yet been completed at the time of the previous joint audit.
1)
A Czech taxable person acquired goods worth EUR 22 686 from a German taxable person in the first quarter of 2005.
The Czech taxpayer did not declare the acquisition in his UST statement, which included a period of time not a UST identification number, but only had a tax number for domestic German transactions.
By means of international assistance under Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the Czech competent FA had received information that, under German VAT law, the supplier of intra-Community goods did not require a UST identification number in order to benefit from the exemption from intra-Community supplies of goods.
The Czech Court of Auditors' audit showed that, according to the examination of the Czech competent FA, the Czech taxpayer made an additional UST declaration declaring the acquisition of goods of the above value while claiming his right to deduct the same amount.
2)
A Czech taxable person is alleged to have acquired goods worth EUR 12 561 from a German taxable person in the fourth quarter of 2004.
However, he stated that he did not acquire the goods and therefore did not explain in his UST statement either.
The German Financial Administration, citing a provision of Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, declined to process the request because the turnover associated with the acquisition did not exceed the threshold of EUR 15 000.
As the Czech FA was unable to obtain any documentation, the tax audit remained without result and the original tax fixing remained in place.
The Czech Court of Auditors' review showed that the Czech FA received from Germany two practical information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, according to which the German taxable person charged the goods in question to a Slovak addressee.
The Czech taxable person acquired the goods from the Slovak taxable person and stated the acquisition in his regular UST statement for the month of October 2004.
3)
A Czech taxpayer is alleged to have acquired a car worth EUR 48 500 from a German taxpayer in the fourth quarter of 2004.
However, he did not declare a intra-Community acquisition.
He had also not made a UST statement since August 2004. Therefore, the FA set the UST at CZK 0 for the quarter concerned.
On the basis of information transmitted from Germany in the course of the international exchange of information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the FA called on the taxable person to submit a subsequent tax return in March 2007, which the taxable person failed to do so.
The audit found that in 2007 the FA had carried out further audit operations in this tax case. In doing so, it had found that the passenger car concerned had been sold by the taxpayer to a second-hand car dealer in the CZ.
The Czech FA carried out an incentive for the tax period December 2004, setting additional taxes of CZK 295 379 for the purchase and resale of goods from another Member State.
The Czech competent court decided to open insolvency proceedings on the assets of the Czech taxpayer; An insolvency administrator has been appointed.
In the absence of significant assets, the outstanding tax liability is likely to be unequivocal.
4)
A Czech taxpayer is alleged to have delivered new vehicles (passenger cars) to Germany in the fourth quarter of 2004 and in the first quarter of 2005 in the total value of EUR 198 167.
The answer to a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003 stated that the German taxpayer was subject to a tax penalty procedure in Germany.
The Federal Court of Auditors' audit found that evidence of involvement of the German taxpayer in scams existed after the procedure was completed.
Intra-Community sales of goods were subject to taxation of EUR 182 424 (2004) and EUR 369 690 (2005).
The Czech Court of Auditors' audit found that the Czech taxable person was involved in carousel fraud with new vehicles.
On the basis of information provided by the German Financial Administration, a UST audit of the Czech taxpayer took place for the tax periods of April, May and June 2005.
Based on the test findings and information from the international exchange of information, the FA established additional CZK 703 031 for May 2005 and CZK 726 551 for June 2005.
5)
Czech taxable person A is alleged to have acquired a total value of EUR 58 000 from a German taxable person in February 2005.
The German taxpayer is alleged to have delivered a machine worth EUR 88 027 to the Czech taxpayer B in the third quarter of 2004. B, however, denied the acquisition.
The Czech Court of Auditors' audit found that B had acquired the machine from a German company established in the CZ.
The Czech taxable person A did not state the acquisition of the goods from that German taxable person in his UST statement.
The German FA's response to a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003 showed that the German taxable person had not made a intra-Community supply of a machine worth EUR 58 000 but rather a delivery within the CZ.
In the audit, the Bundesrechnungshof found that the intra-Community delivery of the machine was classified as domestic delivery after the completion of an operational audit and that the UST exemption was subsequently failed.
6)
A German taxable person is alleged to have delivered goods worth EUR 11 600 to a Czech taxable person in the third quarter of 2004.
The goods were acquired and later, d. I.e. in 2005, sold in Germany.
The Czech Court of Auditors' audit showed that the Czech FA had carried out its assessment on the basis of a supplementary UST declaration, which provided an inadmissible acquisition from another Member State, including the acquisition of the abovementioned amount.
The Bundesgerichtshof found that after receiving a reply to a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the German FA corrected the German taxpayer's UST declaration and established additional UST of EUR 1 600.
Due to the resale of the goods in Germany and the corresponding UST estimate there, an inspection is underway.
The ZM of the German taxpayer has so far not been corrected, since in Germany only the taxable person who surrendered the ZM can correct it.
7)
The Czech Competent FA received from the German Financial Administration a request for information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003 on the question of the acquisition of a car worth 47 400 euros by a Czech taxpayer in February 2005.
Following an audit for the 2005 tax period, the Czech FA established the Czech taxpayer's tax liability at CZK 0 and informed the German FA that it could not confirm the Czech taxpayer's acquisition of the car.
The Czech Court of Auditors' audit showed that the registration of the Czech UST obligee had been deleted because it had not complied with its tax obligations.
The Czech FA had forwarded the documents to the Czech police.
The German taxpayer has so far failed to correct his information in the ZM but has appealed against the tax fine.
8)
According to MIAS10, between the third quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005, a German taxable person supplied a Czech taxable person with a total value of 33 205 euros, which, however, did not declare it an intra-Community acquisition.
The Czech Court of Auditors' audit found that the Czech FA examined the reasons for the inconsistencies.
The Czech taxpayer made repeated subsequent UST statements for the first quarter of 2005.
However, the Czech FA was unable to clarify the difference in the amount of CZK 134 273 in the third quarter of 2004 to the first quarter of 2005. This was justified by the fact that transactions for individual quarters could not be accurately allocated, and accepted the UST statements issued.
9)
A German taxable person had delivered goods worth EUR 46 854 to a Czech taxable person in the third quarter of 2004.
For the same period, the Czech taxable person declared the intra-Community acquisition of goods worth only EUR 14 856.
As part of the intergovernmental exchange of information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the Czech FA verified the actual value of the delivery.
The German reply to this question sent three invoices representing a total value of EUR 31 998 delivered, i.e. That is, an amount equal to the difference between the acquisition declared by the Czech taxpayer and the MIAS data.
According to the outcome of the Czech Court of Auditors' review, the Czech taxpayer submitted a subsequent UST statement for the July 2004 tax period following repeated warnings from the FA in January 2007.
By means of this declaration, the taxable person at the same time claimed his right to deduct VAT. His tax liability for the tax period in question therefore remained unchanged.
The audit confirmed that most of the tax procedures on the transactions selected for the audit had been completed and that the financial administrations in the CZ and Germany respectively had taken appropriate measures (including: Subsequent USt fixtures or prevention of pre-tax refunds).
4.3 Examination of selected cases of intra-Community dumped transactions
4.3.1 Findings in the Czech Republic
EUROCANET may be a significant source of information to identify eligible taxpayers in the Member State of acquisition.
In the CZ, early warning information from EUROCANET is verified by the competent FA to the acquirers.
Since the first quarter of 2008, CZ has set up information on transactions and taxable suppliers that are considered to be eligible for the EUROCANET system.
Nine Czech taxpayers were selected for the audit,
Which had been entered into EUROCANET by the financial administrations of other Member States either as suppliers or acquirers.
