Since the German financial administration did not participate in the exchange of data via EUROCANET, it could not be determined whether suppliers with German UST identification number were classified as risk-prone by the German financial administration.
The audit found both normal business incidents and those involving suspicion of carousel fraud or other UST fraud.
In the cases in question, the CMO exchanged information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003:
z. B.:
• The Federal Republic of Germany did not find any suspicion of risk-related transactions when examining the early warning information.
The taxpayers concerned were continuously monitored because their data were stored in EUROCANET.
• The CMO failed to demonstrate breaches of the rules on the calculation of the taxable amount and of the UST on the basis of the records submitted, although they identified inconsistencies in the transport and storage of the goods or discovered commercial relations with letter box companies from other Member States.
• The review of individual transactions was complicated because certain taxpayers did not cooperate with the CMO and could not be contacted either.
The competent NGOs reviewed most of the dumped taxpayers and transactions listed in EUROCANET's early declarations.
However, their ability to verify dumped transactions, especially so-called missing traders, is limited.
In particular, a mere examination of the documents can hardly provide evidence of fraudulent action by the taxpayer.
Stricter requirements for registration of taxpayers for UST purposes and greater flexibility in deleting registrations would be helpful to combat UST fraud.
The taxable persons involved in fraudulent carousel transactions can be registered for the purpose of the UST in order to prejudge EU-wide fictitious supplies of goods or formally issue correct tax evidence to other taxable persons, by which they then claim unauthorised right to deduct VAT.
In the event of suspicion of carousel fraud related to imports and exports, it is recommended that customs and tax authorities cooperate more closely in order to monitor the nature of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final customer.
Member States may participate in EUROCANET on a voluntary basis.
